export const questionBank16 = [
  {q:"A company runs a three-tier web application (web, app, database). The web tier runs on EC2 behind an ALB in public subnets. The app tier runs on EC2 in private subnets. The database is RDS in private subnets. The app tier needs to call external APIs on the internet. What is the MINIMUM infrastructure change?", opts:["Add an Internet Gateway to the VPC","Add a NAT Gateway in a public subnet and add a route in the app tier's private subnet route table to the NAT Gateway","Move the app tier to public subnets","Use a VPC endpoint for external APIs"], correct:1, exp:"Private subnet instances need a NAT Gateway (in a public subnet) to reach the internet for outbound-only traffic. The NAT Gateway performs address translation. Add a route 0.0.0.0/0 → NAT Gateway ID in the private subnet's route table. The IGW already exists (web tier uses it). VPC endpoints only work for AWS services, not arbitrary external APIs. Moving to public subnets exposes the app tier unnecessarily.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon SQS Standard queue. Messages are processed by a fleet of EC2 consumers. They notice some messages are processed twice, causing duplicate orders. What is the MOST reliable fix?", opts:["Switch to SQS FIFO queue (exactly-once processing)","Increase the visibility timeout","Implement idempotency in the consumer (check if order ID already processed before processing)","Use Long Polling to reduce duplicate deliveries"], correct:2, exp:"SQS Standard queues provide at-least-once delivery — duplicates are possible. The MOST reliable fix is idempotent processing: before processing, check if the message/order was already handled (using a DynamoDB table or database constraint). FIFO queues provide exactly-once but have a 3,000 msg/sec limit and may not fit all use cases. Idempotency works regardless of queue type and is a best practice for any distributed system.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company has an on-premises Active Directory with 5,000 users. They want these users to access the AWS Management Console using their existing corporate credentials (SSO). What is the recommended approach?", opts:["Create 5,000 IAM users and sync passwords periodically","Use AWS IAM Identity Center (SSO) with AD Connector connecting to on-premises Active Directory","Use SAML 2.0 federation with ADFS (Active Directory Federation Services) to IAM roles","Both B and C work — IAM Identity Center is the newer recommended approach"], correct:3, exp:"Both approaches work: (1) IAM Identity Center (formerly AWS SSO) with AD Connector provides SSO to AWS Console and applications with centralized management. (2) ADFS + SAML federation to IAM roles is the traditional approach. AWS recommends IAM Identity Center for new implementations — it's simpler to manage, supports multi-account access, and integrates with permission sets. Both eliminate the need for IAM users.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company runs an application that stores session data in an RDS MySQL database. Under load, the sessions table becomes a bottleneck (frequent reads/writes of small JSON documents, ~1KB each). What is the BEST solution to improve session management performance?", opts:["Add RDS Read Replicas for session reads","Move session data to ElastiCache Redis (sub-millisecond latency, designed for session stores)","Increase RDS instance size","Shard the sessions table across multiple RDS instances"], correct:1, exp:"ElastiCache Redis is purpose-built for session management: sub-millisecond read/write latency, automatic key expiration (TTL for session timeout), and handles millions of operations per second. Sessions are small key-value documents — perfect for Redis. RDS is overkill for this access pattern and adds unnecessary latency (milliseconds vs microseconds). Redis also supports clustering for horizontal scaling.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company has a Lambda function that processes records from a Kinesis Data Stream. The stream has 10 shards. They want to process each shard's records in parallel within the Lambda function to increase throughput. How many concurrent Lambda invocations will there be by default?", opts:["1 (one Lambda per stream)","10 (one Lambda invocation per shard)","Unlimited (Lambda scales independently of shards)","100 (10 shards × 10 parallelization factor)"], correct:1, exp:"By default, Lambda processes each Kinesis shard with ONE concurrent invocation — maintaining ordering within each shard. With 10 shards = 10 concurrent Lambda invocations. To increase parallelism, use the ParallelizationFactor (1-10) which allows multiple Lambda invocations per shard (sacrificing strict ordering within the shard). With factor 10: 10 shards × 10 = 100 concurrent invocations. Default is 1 invocation per shard.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses CloudFormation to deploy infrastructure. A stack update fails midway (3 of 7 resources updated successfully). What happens by default?", opts:["The stack remains in a partially updated state","CloudFormation automatically rolls back ALL changes — reverting the 3 updated resources to their previous state (entire stack returns to previous known-good state)","Only the failed resource is rolled back","The stack is deleted and must be recreated"], correct:1, exp:"CloudFormation automatic rollback on failure is the default behavior. If any resource update fails, CloudFormation rolls back ALL changes made during that update — the entire stack returns to its previous state. This ensures stacks are never left in an inconsistent, partially-updated state. You can disable rollback for debugging (--disable-rollback), but production stacks should always roll back on failure.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company needs to migrate 50TB of data from on-premises to S3. They have a 1 Gbps Direct Connect link. How long will the transfer take, and is there a faster option?", opts:["~5 days over Direct Connect (1Gbps = ~10TB/day). Use AWS Snowball Edge for faster transfer.","~50 days over Direct Connect. Snowball required.","~5 days over Direct Connect. This is fast enough — no need for Snowball.","~1 day over Direct Connect. No alternatives needed."], correct:2, exp:"1 Gbps = ~125 MB/s = ~10.8 TB/day (theoretical max). 50TB ÷ 10.8 TB/day ≈ 5 days. With protocol overhead, realistically 5-7 days. This is reasonable for most use cases. Snowball Edge (80TB capacity) takes 1 week for shipping + loading + shipping back. For 50TB with 1Gbps Direct Connect, the network transfer is comparable speed to Snowball. Snowball becomes clearly better when: bandwidth is lower, data is larger (100TB+), or the link is shared with production traffic.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company hosts a static website on S3 with CloudFront. They want to restrict access so only users from specific countries (US, Canada, UK) can access the site. How is this implemented?", opts:["S3 bucket policy with IP-based conditions for each country's IP ranges","CloudFront Geographic Restrictions (Geo-Restriction) — configure an allowlist of US, CA, GB country codes","WAF Geographic Match rule attached to the CloudFront distribution","Both B and C work — WAF provides more granular control (can combine geo with other conditions)"], correct:3, exp:"Both work: (1) CloudFront Geo-Restriction uses CloudFront's built-in GeoIP database to allow/block by country — simple allowlist/blocklist. (2) WAF Geographic Match on CloudFront allows combining country restrictions with other rules (rate limiting, SQL injection protection, IP reputation). WAF is more flexible if you need multiple conditions. For simple country-only restriction, CloudFront Geo-Restriction is sufficient.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Organizations with 50 accounts. They want to prevent ANY account from launching EC2 instances in ap-southeast-1 (Singapore) region due to data sovereignty requirements. What is the MOST effective organizational control?", opts:["IAM policies in each account denying ec2:RunInstances in ap-southeast-1","Service Control Policy (SCP) attached to the Organization root denying ec2:RunInstances when region = ap-southeast-1","AWS Config rule flagging non-compliant instances","Remove ap-southeast-1 from the account's enabled regions"], correct:1, exp:"SCPs are the ONLY way to enforce preventive controls across ALL accounts in an Organization. An SCP with Deny on ec2:* (or all actions) with Condition StringEquals aws:RequestedRegion = ap-southeast-1 prevents ALL principals (including account root) from using that region. IAM policies must be maintained per-account and can be overridden by admins. SCPs are organizational guardrails that cannot be overridden within member accounts.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company runs a containerized microservices application on ECS Fargate. One service experiences memory pressure — it occasionally gets OOMKilled (Out of Memory). The service normally uses 1.5GB but spikes to 3GB during peak processing. The task is configured with 2GB memory. What should they do?", opts:["Increase the task memory to 4GB (accommodate peak + buffer)","Add an Application Auto Scaling policy on the ECS service to scale out during peak","Use ECS Service Auto Scaling with memory utilization target","Both A (right-size the task) AND B (scale out to distribute load) — choose based on whether peak memory is per-request or total-load driven"], correct:3, exp:"If the 3GB spike is from a single large request/operation: increase task memory to 4GB (the task needs more memory per instance). If the spike is from many concurrent requests: scale out the service (more tasks share the load, each stays under 2GB). Usually it's a combination — right-size the task memory for single-operation peaks AND scale out for load. OOMKill means the task exceeded its hard limit — immediate fix is increasing the limit.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon Cognito User Pools for authentication. They want to allow users to sign in with their Google, Facebook, or Apple accounts in addition to email/password. What Cognito feature supports this?", opts:["Cognito Identity Pools (Federated Identities)","Cognito User Pool Social Identity Providers (built-in OAuth2 integration with Google, Facebook, Apple, Amazon)","Custom Lambda triggers for each provider","SAML federation with each social provider"], correct:1, exp:"Cognito User Pools have built-in support for Social Identity Providers (IdPs): Google, Facebook, Apple, Amazon, and any OIDC provider. Configuration: register your app with the social provider, add provider credentials to Cognito, and users see social login buttons on the hosted UI. After social login, users get the same Cognito tokens as email/password users. Identity Pools are for granting AWS credentials, not user authentication.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses S3 for storing application logs. They currently have a single bucket with ALL logs from ALL applications (100+ applications). Finding logs for a specific application on a specific date requires scanning millions of objects. How should they restructure for efficient querying with Athena?", opts:["Create separate buckets per application","Use S3 prefix structure: s3://bucket/app={app_name}/year={YYYY}/month={MM}/day={DD}/ (Hive-style partitioning for Athena)","Tag each object with application name and date (S3 tags can't be queried by Athena)","Use S3 Inventory to build an index"], correct:1, exp:"Hive-style partitioning (key=value/ prefix structure) is recognized by Athena/Glue for partition pruning. Query WHERE app='myapp' AND year='2024' AND month='01' only scans objects under that specific prefix — not the entire bucket. This reduces scan volume by 99%+ and directly reduces Athena costs (pay per TB scanned). S3 tags are NOT queryable by Athena. Separate buckets would work but are harder to manage at scale.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company uses EBS gp3 volumes for their EC2 database instances. They need consistent sub-millisecond latency for a high-performance database. gp3 provides single-digit millisecond latency but they need better. Which EBS volume type should they use?", opts:["io2 Block Express (sub-millisecond latency, up to 256,000 IOPS, designed for critical databases)","gp3 with maximum provisioned IOPS (16,000 — still single-digit ms latency)","Instance Store (lowest latency but ephemeral — data lost on stop/terminate)","io1 (better than gp3 but not sub-millisecond)"], correct:0, exp:"io2 Block Express provides sub-millisecond latency with up to 256,000 IOPS per volume. It's designed for the most demanding databases (Oracle, SAP HANA, large MongoDB). Instance Store provides the absolute lowest latency (microseconds) but data is EPHEMERAL — not suitable as a primary database volume. io2 Block Express gives the best of both: extreme performance + durability. Available on Nitro-based instances (R5b, etc.).", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Transfer Family (SFTP) to allow external partners to upload files to S3. They need to ensure each partner can ONLY access their own folder (prefix) in the bucket. How is this access scoping implemented?", opts:["Separate S3 buckets per partner","AWS Transfer Family logical directories with IAM role-based access — each user maps to a role with policy scoped to their S3 prefix","Application-level access control in a Lambda function","IP-based restrictions in the bucket policy"], correct:1, exp:"AWS Transfer Family supports per-user IAM roles. Each user (partner) gets a role with an S3 policy allowing access ONLY to their prefix: s3:*Object on arn:aws:s3:::bucket/partner-name/*. Logical directory mappings hide the actual S3 structure — partners see /files which maps to s3://bucket/partner-name/. This provides strong isolation using IAM without separate buckets or application logic.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon Redshift for their data warehouse. Query performance has degraded over time. The DBA notices many queries perform full table scans even when they filter on the 'order_date' column. What is the MOST likely fix?", opts:["Add an index on order_date (Redshift doesn't have traditional indexes)","Set order_date as the SORTKEY for the table (enables zone map filtering, dramatically reducing scanned blocks)","Increase Redshift cluster size","Use VACUUM to reclaim space"], correct:1, exp:"Redshift uses SORTKEYS instead of traditional indexes. When a column is a sortkey, Redshift maintains zone maps (min/max per block) and skips blocks that can't contain matching rows. For order_date queries with date range filters, a SORTKEY on order_date enables block skipping — reading only relevant blocks instead of all blocks. VACUUM is needed after many deletes/updates but doesn't solve the full-scan pattern. Redshift has no traditional B-tree indexes.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company has a Lambda function triggered by API Gateway. The function connects to RDS PostgreSQL. Under load (1000 concurrent requests), they see 'too many connections' errors from RDS. The RDS instance supports max 500 connections. What is the solution?", opts:["Increase RDS max_connections parameter","Use RDS Proxy — it pools and shares database connections across Lambda invocations (reducing 1000 Lambda connections to ~50 actual DB connections)","Reduce Lambda concurrent execution limit to 500","Use connection pooling within each Lambda invocation (ineffective — each invocation is isolated)"], correct:1, exp:"RDS Proxy is purpose-built for this problem. It maintains a connection pool to RDS and multiplexes thousands of Lambda connections into a small number of actual database connections. 1000 concurrent Lambda invocations each open a connection to RDS Proxy, but the proxy maintains only ~50-100 persistent connections to RDS. It also handles connection draining, failover, and IAM authentication. This is THE solution for Lambda + RDS at scale.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company has an S3 bucket in account A. A Lambda function in account B needs to read objects from this bucket. What is required for cross-account access?", opts:["Only a bucket policy on account A's bucket allowing account B's Lambda role","Only the Lambda's IAM role in account B having s3:GetObject permission for the bucket","BOTH: bucket policy in account A allowing access AND the Lambda role in account B having S3 permissions (both sides must grant access for cross-account)","Share the bucket via AWS RAM"], correct:2, exp:"Cross-account S3 access requires BOTH: (1) The resource policy (bucket policy) in account A must allow the Lambda role ARN from account B, AND (2) the Lambda role in account B must have IAM permissions for s3:GetObject on the bucket. If either side is missing, access is denied. This is the fundamental cross-account access model in AWS — both the resource owner AND the principal's account must grant permission.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company runs Aurora MySQL with a primary instance and 2 read replicas. The primary fails. What happens automatically?", opts:["The application must manually failover to a replica","Aurora automatically promotes one of the read replicas to primary (failover completes in ~30 seconds). The cluster endpoint automatically points to the new primary.","A new primary is provisioned from the cluster volume (takes 5-10 minutes)","The cluster becomes read-only until manual intervention"], correct:1, exp:"Aurora automatic failover promotes an existing read replica to primary, typically in ~30 seconds. Aurora's shared storage architecture means no data replication is needed — the promoted replica immediately has access to all data. The cluster writer endpoint automatically resolves to the new primary — applications using the cluster endpoint don't need configuration changes. Failover priority can be configured (tier 0-15) to control which replica is promoted.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Config to monitor compliance. They want to automatically remediate non-compliant resources — for example, if an S3 bucket is created without encryption, automatically enable encryption. How is this configured?", opts:["Config rule with manual remediation via Lambda","AWS Config Automatic Remediation using SSM Automation documents — when a rule evaluates non-compliant, it triggers an SSM document to fix the resource","EventBridge rule on Config compliance change events → Lambda function","Both B and C work — Config has built-in automatic remediation, or you can build custom via EventBridge"], correct:3, exp:"Both approaches work: (1) AWS Config Automatic Remediation links a Config rule to an SSM Automation document. When a resource becomes non-compliant, the document executes automatically (e.g., AWS-EnableS3BucketEncryption). (2) EventBridge can capture Config compliance change events and trigger Lambda for custom remediation logic. Config's built-in remediation is simpler for standard fixes (pre-built SSM docs exist). EventBridge + Lambda is more flexible for complex custom remediation.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses Elastic Beanstalk to deploy a Node.js application. They want to deploy new versions with zero downtime. Which deployment policy should they use?", opts:["All at once (fastest but causes downtime)","Rolling (partial downtime during deployment)","Immutable (zero downtime — launches new instances in a new ASG, shifts traffic after health checks pass, terminates old instances)","Blue/Green with DNS swap (zero downtime but requires Route 53 configuration)"], correct:2, exp:"Immutable deployment: launches new instances with the new version in a temporary ASG, waits for health checks to pass, then moves new instances to the main ASG and terminates old ones. Zero downtime and safe rollback (terminate new instances if they fail). Rolling has reduced capacity during deployment. Blue/Green works but requires more infrastructure and DNS swap. Immutable is the recommended zero-downtime policy within Beanstalk.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses CloudTrail for API audit logging. A security engineer needs to find who deleted an S3 bucket 3 months ago. Where should they look?", opts:["CloudTrail Event History (only retains 90 days and only management events)","CloudTrail Trail logs stored in S3 (configured to log management events indefinitely, searchable with Athena)","S3 access logs (don't log DeleteBucket API)","CloudWatch Logs (only if CloudTrail is configured to deliver to CloudWatch)"], correct:1, exp:"CloudTrail Event History provides 90 days of management events in the console — but 3 months ago is at the edge. If a Trail is configured to deliver logs to S3, logs are retained indefinitely (based on bucket lifecycle) and searchable with Athena. Query: SELECT * FROM cloudtrail_logs WHERE eventname='DeleteBucket' AND eventtime > '2024-04-01'. Always configure a Trail to S3 for long-term audit retention beyond 90 days.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company needs a managed Apache Kafka service for event streaming. They currently run self-managed Kafka on EC2 (6 brokers). Which AWS service provides managed Kafka?", opts:["Amazon Kinesis Data Streams (different from Kafka)","Amazon MSK (Managed Streaming for Apache Kafka) — fully managed Kafka service compatible with existing Kafka clients/tools","Amazon MQ (managed RabbitMQ/ActiveMQ, not Kafka)","Amazon EventBridge (serverless event bus, not Kafka)"], correct:1, exp:"Amazon MSK provides fully managed Apache Kafka: broker provisioning, patching, monitoring, and automatic recovery. Existing Kafka producers/consumers work without code changes — MSK provides the same Apache Kafka APIs. Migration from self-managed Kafka: point existing clients to MSK bootstrap servers. MSK Serverless also available (scales automatically). Kinesis is similar in concept but different API/ecosystem. MQ is for traditional message queuing (RabbitMQ/ActiveMQ).", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses AWS WAF on their ALB. They want to block requests that contain SQL injection attempts in query parameters AND in the request body. How should the WAF rule be configured?", opts:["Two separate rules — one for query string, one for body","Single rule with SQL injection match statement inspecting ALL request components (query string, body, URI, headers)","AWS WAF can only inspect query strings, not request bodies","Use AWS Shield instead for SQL injection protection"], correct:1, exp:"WAF SQL injection match statements can inspect multiple request components: query string, body, URI path, headers, and cookies. Configure a single rule with the SQLi match condition set to inspect both 'Query string' and 'Body'. WAF uses sophisticated patterns to detect SQL injection attempts (UNION SELECT, OR 1=1, comment sequences, etc.). Shield is DDoS protection, not application-layer attack protection. WAF handles OWASP Top 10 web attacks.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company has an Auto Scaling group that launches instances using a launch template. The instances need a specific EBS volume for data (/dev/sdf, 500GB, gp3). Where is this configured?", opts:["UserData script that creates and attaches an EBS volume after launch","Block device mappings in the launch template (specify additional volumes with device name, size, volume type, IOPS, throughput)","Auto Scaling lifecycle hook that attaches a volume","AWS Config rule that ensures EBS volume attachment"], correct:1, exp:"Launch template Block Device Mappings define EBS volumes that are automatically created and attached when an instance launches. Configure: DeviceName=/dev/sdf, VolumeSize=500, VolumeType=gp3, IOPS and Throughput as needed. The volume is created and attached automatically with the instance — no scripts or hooks needed. Volumes defined in block device mappings are also automatically deleted on instance termination (if DeleteOnTermination=true).", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses Route 53 for DNS. Their application has a primary deployment in us-east-1 and a DR deployment in eu-west-1. They want traffic to go to us-east-1 normally, but automatically switch to eu-west-1 if us-east-1 is unhealthy. Which routing policy?", opts:["Weighted routing (50/50 split)","Latency-based routing with health checks","Failover routing policy (primary/secondary with health check on primary)","Geolocation routing"], correct:2, exp:"Route 53 Failover routing is designed for active-passive DR: Primary record points to us-east-1, Secondary record points to eu-west-1. A health check monitors the primary endpoint. When the health check fails, Route 53 automatically responds with the secondary (eu-west-1) IP. When primary recovers, traffic returns to us-east-1. This is the standard active-passive DNS failover pattern.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company has 200 microservices deployed on EKS. They need distributed tracing to understand request flow across services (which service called which, where latency occurs). Which AWS service provides distributed tracing?", opts:["CloudWatch Logs (logs per service, no trace correlation)","AWS X-Ray (distributed tracing — traces requests across services, shows service map, identifies bottlenecks)","CloudWatch Metrics (aggregate metrics, no per-request tracing)","AWS CloudMap (service discovery, not tracing)"], correct:1, exp:"AWS X-Ray provides distributed tracing: instruments each service to generate trace segments, correlates them into end-to-end traces using a trace ID, and visualizes the request flow as a service map. Shows: which services were called, latency at each hop, error rates, and bottlenecks. X-Ray SDK or OpenTelemetry auto-instruments popular frameworks. Essential for debugging latency in microservices architectures.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses EFS (Elastic File System) for shared storage across 20 EC2 instances. They notice high read latency during peak hours. The filesystem uses the default Bursting Throughput mode. What should they change?", opts:["Switch to Provisioned Throughput mode (guaranteed throughput regardless of storage size)","Switch to Elastic Throughput mode (automatically scales throughput based on workload, pay per use)","Add more EC2 instances to distribute the reads","Increase the amount of data stored (Bursting mode throughput scales with storage size)"], correct:1, exp:"EFS Elastic Throughput (released 2022) automatically scales throughput up to 10 GB/s read and 3 GB/s write based on actual workload — pay only for what you use. No need to predict and provision capacity. Bursting mode provides throughput proportional to storage size (which may be insufficient). Provisioned mode requires upfront capacity planning. Elastic is the best choice for unpredictable or spiky workloads — combines the benefits of both.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company wants to enforce that ALL EC2 instances launched in their account MUST use encrypted EBS volumes. How can they enforce this at the account level?", opts:["IAM policy denying ec2:RunInstances without encryption","Enable EBS encryption by default in the account settings (all new EBS volumes are automatically encrypted)","AWS Config rule detecting unencrypted volumes","SCP requiring encryption parameter"], correct:1, exp:"'EBS encryption by default' is an account-level setting (per region). Once enabled, ALL new EBS volumes and snapshots are automatically encrypted using the default CMK (or a specified CMK). No IAM policy needed, no possibility of creating unencrypted volumes. This is the simplest, most reliable enforcement — even if someone forgets to specify encryption, it happens automatically. AWS Config can detect but not prevent. IAM policies can be complex to maintain.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses SQS FIFO queue. They send messages with the same MessageGroupId. What does this guarantee?", opts:["Messages are delivered to multiple consumers in parallel","Messages with the same MessageGroupId are processed in EXACTLY the order they were sent (strict ordering within the group). Only one consumer processes messages from a group at a time.","Messages are deduplicated globally","Messages are encrypted automatically"], correct:1, exp:"FIFO queues with MessageGroupId provide strict ordering WITHIN a group. All messages in the same group are delivered in order, and only one consumer processes that group at a time. Different MessageGroupIds can be processed in parallel (by different consumers). This enables ordered processing per entity (e.g., per customer_id) while maintaining parallelism across entities. It's like a partition key in Kinesis.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company wants to ensure their S3 bucket can NEVER be made public, even by an administrator who modifies the bucket policy. What AWS feature provides this absolute guarantee?", opts:["S3 bucket policy denying public access (can be modified by admins)","S3 Block Public Access settings at the account level (overrides any bucket policy that grants public access)","IAM policy denying s3:PutBucketPolicy","SCP preventing public bucket policies"], correct:1, exp:"S3 Block Public Access at the ACCOUNT level overrides any bucket-level configuration. Even if someone adds a bucket policy granting public access, the account-level block public access setting rejects public requests. Four settings: BlockPublicAcls, IgnorePublicAcls, BlockPublicPolicy, RestrictPublicBuckets. When set at the account level, they apply to ALL buckets and CANNOT be overridden at the bucket level. This is the strongest guarantee against accidental public exposure.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses CloudFront with an S3 origin. They want to serve private content — only authenticated users with valid tokens should access the files. What CloudFront feature implements this?", opts:["S3 bucket policy restricting to specific IP addresses","CloudFront Signed URLs or Signed Cookies (generated by your application with a private key, verified by CloudFront before serving content)","CloudFront Origin Access Control (restricts S3 access to CloudFront only, not user authentication)","ALB authentication in front of CloudFront"], correct:1, exp:"CloudFront Signed URLs (for individual files) or Signed Cookies (for multiple files/streaming) provide authenticated access. Your application generates signed URLs using a CloudFront key pair. CloudFront validates the signature, expiration, and optional IP restriction before serving content. OAC restricts S3 to CloudFront (origin access) but doesn't authenticate end users. Signed URLs/Cookies provide USER-level access control.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses DynamoDB with on-demand capacity mode. They experience throttling during a sudden traffic spike (10x normal in 30 seconds). On-demand is supposed to handle spikes. Why is it throttling?", opts:["On-demand has no limits","DynamoDB on-demand instantly scales to double the previous peak, then adapts further over time. A 10x spike exceeds the instant scaling capability — the table needs to 'warm up' to higher traffic levels gradually.","The table has a provisioned capacity limit that wasn't removed","DynamoDB is experiencing an outage"], correct:1, exp:"DynamoDB on-demand instantly accommodates up to double the previous traffic peak. Beyond that, it scales further but takes time (minutes). A sudden 10x spike exceeds the instant 2x buffer. Solutions: (1) gradually increase traffic to warm up the table, (2) switch to provisioned with higher capacity for expected peak, or (3) if spikes are predictable, use provisioned with Application Auto Scaling that pre-scales. This 2x instant scaling limit is a key on-demand consideration.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Backup to manage backups across multiple services (RDS, EBS, EFS, DynamoDB). They need to copy backups to a different AWS region for disaster recovery. How is cross-region backup configured?", opts:["Manually export and import backups between regions","AWS Backup supports cross-region copy in the backup plan — configure a copy rule specifying the destination region","Use S3 cross-region replication for all backups","Lambda function triggered by backup completion to copy to another region"], correct:1, exp:"AWS Backup natively supports cross-region copy. In the backup plan, add a Copy action specifying the destination region and optional lifecycle (move to cold storage, delete after X days). Works for: RDS snapshots, EBS snapshots, EFS backups, DynamoDB backups, and more. Fully automated — no scripts or Lambda needed. This is the standard AWS DR approach: automated cross-region backup copies.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company runs a real-time bidding platform that needs to respond to bid requests within 10 milliseconds. The application looks up bidder preferences stored in a database. Which database provides consistent single-digit millisecond reads?", opts:["RDS MySQL (typically 2-5ms reads for simple queries)","DynamoDB (consistent single-digit millisecond reads at any scale)","DynamoDB with DAX (DynamoDB Accelerator — microsecond reads from in-memory cache)","ElastiCache Redis (sub-millisecond reads)"], correct:2, exp:"For 10ms TOTAL response time (including application logic, network, etc.), the database read must be microseconds, not milliseconds. DAX provides microsecond response times by caching DynamoDB reads in memory. DynamoDB alone is single-digit milliseconds (could use 5-8ms of the 10ms budget). DAX with DynamoDB gives microsecond reads — leaving ample time for application logic within the 10ms budget. ElastiCache also works but requires separate data management.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Lambda functions that share common code (authentication library, logging utilities). Each function includes this shared code in its deployment package, making packages large and updates difficult. What is the recommended approach for sharing code?", opts:["Copy the shared code into each function's package","Lambda Layers — package shared code as a Layer, attach it to multiple functions. Updating the layer updates all functions on next deployment.","Put shared code in S3 and download at runtime","Use a monorepo with shared node_modules"], correct:1, exp:"Lambda Layers allow you to package shared libraries, custom runtimes, or other dependencies separately from function code. Multiple functions can reference the same layer. Benefits: smaller deployment packages, shared code in one place, independent versioning of shared libraries. Each function can use up to 5 layers. Total unzipped size (function + layers) must be ≤250MB. This is the AWS-recommended approach for shared dependencies.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon Athena to query data in S3. Their queries scan 500GB of data but only need 5 columns out of 50. They're paying $2.50 per query ($5/TB scanned). How can they reduce cost by 90%?", opts:["Use S3 Select to pre-filter (only works for simple filtering, not SQL joins)","Convert data from CSV/JSON to Apache Parquet (columnar format) — Athena only reads the 5 needed columns, scanning ~50GB instead of 500GB","Compress the CSV files (reduces storage but Athena still scans all columns)","Use Redshift Spectrum instead of Athena"], correct:1, exp:"Parquet is a columnar format — data is stored by column, not by row. When Athena queries 5 of 50 columns, it reads ONLY those 5 columns' data from S3 (~10% of total data). With CSV/JSON (row format), Athena must read all 500GB even if only 5 columns are needed. Converting to Parquet: 500GB × 10% = 50GB scanned = $0.25/query (90% cost reduction). Parquet also compresses better. This is the #1 Athena cost optimization.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company runs an application on EC2 that needs to call AWS APIs (S3, DynamoDB, SQS). The developer initially hardcoded AWS access keys in the application code. What is the SECURITY BEST PRACTICE?", opts:["Store keys in environment variables (slightly better but still keys on the instance)","Use an IAM Instance Profile (EC2 role) — the instance automatically receives temporary credentials via the metadata service. No keys needed.","Store keys in AWS Secrets Manager","Use AWS KMS to encrypt the keys at rest"], correct:1, exp:"IAM Instance Profiles (EC2 roles) provide temporary credentials automatically rotated by AWS. The SDK automatically retrieves credentials from the instance metadata service (IMDS). No access keys to manage, rotate, or secure. This is the FUNDAMENTAL best practice for EC2 → AWS API authentication. Never use long-term access keys on EC2 instances. Instance profiles provide: automatic rotation, no key management, and least-privilege via IAM policies.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company's application uses a multi-AZ RDS MySQL deployment. During a planned failover test, the application experiences 35 seconds of downtime. They want to reduce this. What can minimize failover time?", opts:["Use RDS Proxy — it maintains a connection pool and routes to the new primary faster, reducing application-perceived downtime to seconds","Increase RDS instance size","Use a Route 53 health check to detect failover faster","Pre-warm the standby instance with read traffic (not possible with Multi-AZ standby)"], correct:0, exp:"RDS Proxy holds a connection pool to the database. During failover, the proxy detects the new primary and redirects connections without the application needing to: detect the failure, close connections, resolve the new DNS, and re-establish connections. This reduces application-perceived downtime from 30-60 seconds to typically <10 seconds. Without a proxy, the DNS change (CNAME update) plus connection re-establishment is what takes 30+ seconds.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company wants to run ML inference (serving predictions) for a computer vision model. The model is 5GB and inference takes 100ms on GPU. They receive 10-1000 requests per second (variable). Which service is MOST cost-effective?", opts:["SageMaker Real-time Endpoints with auto-scaling (always-on GPU instances)","SageMaker Serverless Inference (no GPU support, cold starts)","SageMaker Asynchronous Inference (for long-running inferences, not real-time)","Amazon EC2 GPU instances (g4dn) with Application Auto Scaling behind an ALB"], correct:0, exp:"SageMaker Real-time Endpoints with auto-scaling: scales GPU instances up/down based on invocations per instance. For variable 10-1000 RPS: scales from 1-10+ GPU instances as needed. SageMaker manages model deployment, health checks, and auto-scaling. Serverless inference doesn't support GPU. Async inference is for predictions that can wait (not real-time). EC2 + ALB works but requires more operational management than SageMaker endpoints.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company uses API Gateway REST API with Lambda integration. They notice that API responses are slow (2-3 seconds) for requests that return the same data repeatedly (product catalog). How can they reduce latency for repeated requests?", opts:["Lambda Provisioned Concurrency (helps cold starts, not cache)","Enable API Gateway caching — it caches endpoint responses for a configurable TTL, returning cached responses without invoking Lambda","Add CloudFront in front of API Gateway (adds a CDN layer with caching)","Both B and C add caching at different layers — API Gateway cache for API-level, CloudFront for edge-level"], correct:3, exp:"Both help: (1) API Gateway caching stores responses per API stage, keyed by request path/params. Subsequent identical requests return cached response without Lambda invocation. TTL: 0-3600 seconds. (2) CloudFront in front of API Gateway caches responses at edge locations (closer to users). They can complement each other. For a product catalog, both are beneficial — edge caching for global latency + API caching to reduce Lambda invocations.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses CloudWatch Alarms to monitor their application. They have an alarm for CPU > 80% on their RDS instance. The alarm goes to ALARM state, but they receive no notification. What is missing?", opts:["CloudWatch Alarms don't support notifications","The alarm needs an SNS topic action configured (alarm → SNS → email/SMS/Lambda), and the SNS subscription must be confirmed","The alarm threshold is wrong","RDS doesn't support CloudWatch alarms"], correct:1, exp:"A CloudWatch Alarm has three components: metric/threshold, period/evaluation, and ACTIONS. Actions define what happens when the alarm state changes. Common action: publish to an SNS topic (which then sends email, SMS, triggers Lambda, etc.). If no action is configured, the alarm state changes silently. Also: email subscriptions to SNS topics must be CONFIRMED (click the link in the subscription email). Both missing action and unconfirmed subscription cause silent alarms.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company migrates their Oracle database to Aurora PostgreSQL using DMS. After migration, they discover that stored procedures, triggers, and functions were NOT migrated by DMS. Why?", opts:["DMS doesn't support Oracle as a source","DMS migrates DATA only (tables, rows, indexes) — it does NOT migrate application code (stored procedures, triggers, functions, packages). Use AWS SCT (Schema Conversion Tool) for code objects.","The DMS task was misconfigured","Oracle stored procedures are incompatible with PostgreSQL"], correct:1, exp:"AWS DMS migrates DATA: tables, rows, primary keys, and optionally indexes and LOBs. It does NOT migrate: stored procedures, triggers, functions, views, sequences, or other DATABASE CODE. AWS SCT (Schema Conversion Tool) converts these code objects between source and target engines (e.g., Oracle PL/SQL → PostgreSQL PL/pgSQL). Use SCT FIRST for schema/code conversion, then DMS for data migration. This is a critical DMS limitation to understand.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company needs to process video files uploaded to S3. Each video is 1-5GB and processing takes 20-40 minutes per file. They receive 0-50 uploads per hour (variable). The processing must be cost-effective and complete within 2 hours of upload. Which compute option?", opts:["Lambda (15-minute timeout — can't process 40-minute jobs)","AWS Batch with Spot Instances (cost-effective batch processing, auto-scales from zero, handles variable workload)","EC2 Auto Scaling group (always-on baseline)","Step Functions calling Lambda in a loop"], correct:1, exp:"AWS Batch: scales from ZERO when idle (no cost), uses Spot Instances (60-90% cheaper than On-Demand), handles job queuing, and automatically provisions the right compute for each job. For 20-40 minute jobs with variable 0-50/hour load: Batch launches Spot instances when jobs arrive, processes them, and terminates when done. 2-hour SLA is easily met. Lambda can't run 40 minutes. Always-on EC2 wastes money during idle periods.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company has a VPC with CIDR 10.0.0.0/16. They've used all available IP addresses and need more. They cannot change the existing CIDR. What can they do?", opts:["Create a new VPC and peer it (applications would need to cross the peering connection)","Add a secondary CIDR block to the existing VPC (up to 5 CIDRs per VPC, e.g., add 10.1.0.0/16)","Delete unused ENIs to free IP addresses","Resize the existing CIDR from /16 to /8 (not possible — CIDRs cannot be resized)"], correct:1, exp:"AWS allows adding secondary CIDR blocks to an existing VPC (up to 5 IPv4 CIDRs). Add a non-overlapping CIDR (e.g., 10.1.0.0/16) and create new subnets within it. Existing resources are unaffected. This is the simplest solution — no migration, no peering, same VPC. The secondary CIDR can come from a different RFC 1918 range or even a public IP range you own. VPC CIDRs cannot be modified or expanded once created, but new ones can be added.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses S3 for data lake storage. They want to track all API calls made to their S3 buckets (who did what, when) for security auditing. Which provides the MOST comprehensive S3 API audit trail?", opts:["S3 server access logs (limited fields, not real-time, delivered with delay)","CloudTrail Data Events for S3 (logs every GetObject, PutObject, DeleteObject API call with full request details, IAM identity, source IP, timestamp)","S3 Inventory (lists objects, not API calls)","VPC Flow Logs (network-level, not API-level)"], correct:1, exp:"CloudTrail Data Events for S3 capture EVERY object-level API call: GetObject, PutObject, DeleteObject, CopyObject, etc. Each log entry includes: who (IAM identity/role), what (API call + bucket/key), when (timestamp), where (source IP), and whether it succeeded. This is the definitive S3 security audit trail. S3 access logs are simpler (limited fields, no IAM identity detail) and have delivery delays. CloudTrail Data Events are near-real-time.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses Terraform to manage their AWS infrastructure. They accidentally ran 'terraform destroy' on their production environment, deleting critical resources (RDS, ElastiCache). RDS had automated backups but ElastiCache did not. How can they prevent this in the future?", opts:["Use lifecycle { prevent_destroy = true } on critical resources in Terraform AND enable RDS deletion protection","Enable AWS Backup for all critical resources AND use SCPs to prevent deletion of specific resources","All of: Terraform prevent_destroy, RDS deletion protection, AWS Backup for ElastiCache, and restrict destroy permissions","Only use CloudFormation with termination protection instead of Terraform"], correct:2, exp:"Defense in depth: (1) Terraform prevent_destroy lifecycle rule blocks terraform destroy on specific resources, (2) RDS deletion protection blocks DeleteDBInstance API even if Terraform tries, (3) AWS Backup creates cross-region recovery points for ElastiCache (which doesn't have built-in long-term backups), (4) IAM/SCP restrictions on destroy/delete actions limit who can destroy. Multiple layers ensure no single mistake causes data loss.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses EventBridge (CloudWatch Events) to trigger a Lambda function when an EC2 instance changes state to 'terminated'. They want to clean up DNS records and notify the team. The rule pattern is correct but the Lambda never triggers. What is likely wrong?", opts:["EventBridge can't capture EC2 state changes","The Lambda function needs a resource-based policy allowing EventBridge (events.amazonaws.com) to invoke it","EC2 state changes only go to CloudWatch Events, not EventBridge","The event pattern doesn't match the actual event structure"], correct:1, exp:"For EventBridge to invoke Lambda, the Lambda function must have a resource-based policy allowing the events.amazonaws.com service principal to call lambda:InvokeFunction. This permission is automatically added when you use the console to create the rule, but if created via CLI/Terraform/CloudFormation, you must explicitly add the permission. Without it, EventBridge detects the event but is denied when trying to invoke the target.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose to deliver streaming data to S3. They want the data to arrive in S3 in Parquet format (for efficient Athena querying). The source data is JSON. Can Firehose do this conversion?", opts:["No — Firehose only delivers raw data as-is","Yes — Firehose supports record format conversion: JSON to Parquet or ORC using a Glue Data Catalog table schema for column definitions","Firehose can only compress, not convert formats","You need a Lambda transformation to convert to Parquet"], correct:1, exp:"Kinesis Data Firehose has built-in record format conversion. Configure: source format (JSON), output format (Parquet or ORC), and reference a Glue Data Catalog table for the schema. Firehose automatically converts records before writing to S3. No Lambda needed for this conversion. This is extremely powerful — streaming data arrives in S3 already in the optimal columnar format for Athena/Redshift Spectrum queries.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company needs to ensure that their ECS tasks have EXACTLY one instance of a specific task running per EC2 container instance (like a daemon). What ECS scheduling strategy should they use?", opts:["Replica service with desired count = number of instances","DAEMON scheduling strategy (places exactly one task on each container instance in the cluster, automatically adjusts as instances are added/removed)","Run task with placement constraint distinctInstance","One-off task scheduling"], correct:1, exp:"ECS DAEMON scheduling strategy ensures exactly one copy of the task runs on each container instance. When new instances join the cluster, a task is automatically placed. When instances leave, the task is removed. Use cases: log collection agents (Fluentd), monitoring agents (Datadog), security agents. REPLICA strategy maintains a specific count distributed across instances. DAEMON is specifically for per-host sidecar services.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Fargate for ECS. They need tasks to access a secret stored in Secrets Manager at startup. How should the secret be injected into the container?", opts:["Application code calls Secrets Manager API at startup (requires SDK integration)","ECS task definition 'secrets' property — references Secrets Manager ARN, ECS injects the secret as an environment variable or file at container startup","Store the secret in an S3 file and mount it","Hardcode the secret in the Docker image (terrible practice)"], correct:1, exp:"ECS task definition 'secrets' field (under containerDefinitions) references a Secrets Manager ARN. At task launch, ECS resolves the secret and injects it as an environment variable (valueFrom). The task execution role needs secretsmanager:GetSecretValue permission. Benefits: no SDK code needed, secrets never in image/source code, rotation handled by Secrets Manager, audit trail via CloudTrail. Also works with SSM Parameter Store for non-sensitive config.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company has a VPC with a public subnet and a private subnet. They launch an EC2 instance in the public subnet with a public IP. The instance CANNOT reach the internet. Security group allows all outbound traffic. What is MOST likely missing?", opts:["No Internet Gateway attached to the VPC (or no route to the IGW in the subnet's route table)","The instance needs an Elastic IP, not just a public IP","The NACL is blocking outbound traffic","The instance needs a NAT Gateway"], correct:0, exp:"For internet access from a public subnet, THREE things are required: (1) Internet Gateway attached to the VPC, (2) Route table entry: 0.0.0.0/0 → IGW, (3) Public IP on the instance. If the IGW isn't attached or the route table doesn't have the 0.0.0.0/0 → IGW route, internet access fails despite having a public IP and open security group. This is a foundational VPC networking troubleshooting question.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company operates a global SaaS application. They need a database that supports single-digit millisecond reads and writes globally, with active-active multi-region writes. Which AWS database?", opts:["Aurora Global Database (fast reads globally but writes only to ONE primary region)","DynamoDB Global Tables (active-active multi-region writes with single-digit millisecond performance per region)","RDS Multi-AZ (single region only)","ElastiCache Global Datastore (in-memory cache, not a primary database)"], correct:1, exp:"DynamoDB Global Tables provides active-active multi-region replication. Each region has a full read/write replica. Writes in any region replicate to all others (eventually consistent, typically <1 second). Local reads and writes are single-digit milliseconds. Aurora Global Database has fast cross-region reads but writes must go to a single primary region. For true active-active global writes, DynamoDB Global Tables is the answer.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses Step Functions to orchestrate a complex workflow. One step calls an external API that occasionally takes 30+ minutes to respond. Step Functions has a maximum integration timeout. How should they handle this long-running external call?", opts:["Increase Step Functions timeout (max execution is 1 year but individual integration patterns matter)","Use the Task Token pattern (.waitForTaskToken) — Step Functions pauses the execution, hands a token to the caller, and resumes only when the external system calls back with the token","Use a Wait state followed by a retry loop","Call the API from Lambda (15-minute max, still too short)"], correct:1, exp:"The .waitForTaskToken integration pattern is designed for external long-running operations. Step Functions: (1) sends the task token to the external service (via Lambda/SQS/etc.), (2) PAUSES the execution (no charges while waiting), (3) resumes when the external service calls SendTaskSuccess/SendTaskFailure with the token. Can wait up to 1 year. Perfect for human approvals, external API callbacks, or any asynchronous operation. No polling or timeout issues.", domain:2},
]
